{
  "slug": "ari-asters-eddington-is-a-mirror-like-what-you-see",
  "title": "Ari Aster’s ‘Eddington’ Is a Mirror. Like What You See?",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2025-07-18",
  "runtimeMin": 120,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Amanda Dobbins, with critic Adam Naiman, break down Ari Aster's COVID-era Western 'Eddington,' pair it with Kiyoshi Kurosawa's 'Cloud,' then Sean talks with Aster on his fifth visit to the show.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The news",
      "note": "trailers and fall-festival slates",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "After the Hunt",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "The new Luca Guadagnino movie, whose trailer dropped this week. Sean and Amanda saw it in April and bid it up in the auction; it's a campus sexual-assault/cancel-culture drama starring Julia Roberts, Andrew Garfield, and Ayo Edebiri, out October 10 then wide October 17, and they peg it as a likely Venice/Telluride premiere."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "‘Eddington’",
      "note": "with Adam Naiman",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Eddington",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Ari Aster's fourth feature, an A24 modern Western set in a small New Mexico town in May 2020, where a standoff between sheriff Joe Cross (Joaquin Phoenix) and mayor Ted Garcia (Pedro Pascal) becomes a COVID- and social-media-poisoned powder keg. With Emma Stone, Austin Butler, Luke Grimes, Deirdre O'Connell, Michael Ward, and Clifton Collins Jr., shot by Darius Khondji. It premiered to cool Cannes reviews; Amanda calls it the funniest movie of 2025, Naiman lands on 'mixed feelings but I like it,' Sean thinks it may be Aster's best. They defend it against charges of opportunism, read Antifa 'crisis actors' as Aster's usual hiding-in-plain-sight cult, and tie the homeless character Lodge, the Young Mr. Lincoln finale, and a first-person-shooter climax to a movie about a country that can no longer feel for anyone. Tracking around $5 million opening weekend."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hereditary",
          "year": 2018,
          "note": "Aster's debut, invoked to argue Eddington is 'about the same thing as the other movies': buried family history erupting outward. Naiman half-jokes you could call the new film Hereditary too."
        },
        {
          "title": "Midsommar",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Cited for the cult-in-plain-sight structure and its paralyzed-witness ending, which Eddington echoes with Emma Stone's character drifting into her own pregnancy cult."
        },
        {
          "title": "Beau Is Afraid",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "The three-hour prior feature, treated as the 'blank check' benchmark. They call Eddington more grounded and approachable by comparison, and note Phoenix made more sense to them as Beau's mama's-boy figure."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Cloud’",
      "note": "Adam Naiman on Kiyoshi Kurosawa",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Cloud",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Kiyoshi Kurosawa's 27th feature, his biggest US release (via Sideshow), about an internet reseller/counterfeiter (nickname Ratel, also a word for honey badger) whose ruthless schemes bring the rage of the web literally to his door. Naiman, who rates Kurosawa among the ten greatest living filmmakers, frames it as a companion to Eddington (life lived through screens) that curdles from a Kurosawa-esque thriller into a violent, funny near-apocalypse; Sean calls it 'heat for dumb fucks.' Naiman recommends the non-horror Tokyo Sonata as an entry point."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "Ari Aster",
      "guest": "Ari Aster on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Eddington",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Aster (his fifth appearance) says he wrote a fast first draft in June 2020, 'the movie that Twitter built,' then went back and interviewed New Mexico sheriffs, mayors, and Pueblo officials. Joe Cross is modeled on a real sheriff whose wardrobe Joaquin copied. He wanted a film about living where nobody agrees on what's happening, empathic in oppositional directions, staged as a dark-comedy Western with characters each living in a different movie (High Noon for Joe, Call of Duty for the kid). On JFK's conspiracy fever as a touchstone, Chayefsky's sermonizing as a thing to avoid, having 'a lot of hope but very little confidence,' and a not-quite-sequel with returning characters."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
